After exploring several methods, I am defining outliers as salinity values 3 standard deviations from the weekly salinity average. After graphing this, some outliers still remain so I remove them using filter.

Tiburon Data

Calculate weekly salinity average and sd

eos$date<-as.Date(eos$date, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
eos$week_year<-date2week(eos$date, floor_day=TRUE)
sal_week_av<-aggregate( salinity ~ week_year,eos, mean)
sal_week_sd<-aggregate(salinity~week_year,eos, sd)

Change column names

names(sal_week_av)[names(sal_week_av) == "salinity"] <- "week_sal_av"
names(sal_week_sd)[names(sal_week_sd) == "salinity"] <- "week_sal_sd"

Combine data frames

eos_sal_summary<-cbind(sal_week_av, sal_week_sd)

Add the monthly average and sd columns to the eos df

eos_new<-merge(eos, eos_sal_summary[, c("week_year", "week_sal_av", "week_sal_sd")], by="week_year")

Caluculate 3 standard deviations from monthly average and then remove salinity values that are greater.

eos_new$remove<-(3*eos_new$week_sal_sd)+eos_new$week_sal_av
removed_data<-filter(eos_new, salinity<=remove)

Graph to compare data sets

removed<-ggplot(data = removed_data, mapping = aes(x = date, y = salinity, color=salinity)) + geom_point()  +stat_smooth(colour="green")+ggtitle("Outliers Removed") +  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "plain")) +theme(axis.text=element_text(size=12),axis.title=element_text(size=12,face="plain")) + ylab("Salinity") + xlab("") + theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.background = element_blank(), axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"))

all<-ggplot(data = eos, mapping = aes(x = date, y = salinity, color=salinity)) + geom_point()  +stat_smooth(colour="green")+ggtitle("Raw Data")+  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "plain")) +theme(axis.text=element_text(size=12),axis.title=element_text(size=12,face="plain")) + ylab("Salinity") + xlab("") + theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.background = element_blank(), axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"))

ggarrange(all, removed, ncol=2, nrow=1)

Let’s clean up the environment and keep only the df needed.

rm(list=setdiff(ls(), "removed_data"))
eos_salinity<-removed_data
rm(list=setdiff(ls(), "eos_salinity"))
